	(1976,'_transient__sol_cache_all','a:4:{i:0;a:3:{s:6:\"slider\";a:7:{i:904;a:7:{s:6:\"status\";s:6:\"active\";s:3:\"src\";s:110:\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/30-Image-Carousel-Child-Safety-Slide-1.jpg\";s:5:\"title\";s:52:\"Portrait of teenage boy (13-15) using digital tablet\";s:4:\"link\";s:0:\"\";s:3:\"alt\";s:52:\"Portrait of teenage boy (13-15) using digital tablet\";s:7:\"caption\";s:247:\"Home used to be a sanctuary for children and teens who were bullied at school. In the age of social media, however, being constantly connected means that kids can no longer escape. Here are important warning signs to look for in your children. [1]\";s:4:\"type\";s:5:\"image\";}i:905;a:7:{s:6:\"status\";s:6:\"active\";s:3:\"src\";s:110:\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/30-Image-Carousel-Child-Safety-Slide-2.jpg\";s:5:\"title\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 2\";s:4:\"link\";s:0:\"\";s:3:\"alt\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 2\";s:7:\"caption\";s:254:\"<strong>Avoids technology:</strong> If you notice that your child used to spend a lot of time on Facebook, and now is rarely logging on, something could be wrong. Getting jumpy at a notification for a text or instant message could also spell trouble. [1]\";s:4:\"type\";s:5:\"image\";}i:900;a:7:{s:6:\"status\";s:6:\"active\";s:3:\"src\";s:110:\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/30-Image-Carousel-Child-Safety-Slide-3.jpg\";s:5:\"title\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 3\";s:4:\"link\";s:0:\"\";s:3:\"alt\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 3\";s:7:\"caption\";s:310:\"<strong>Refuses to talk about computer activity:  </strong>Kids will be kids, and sometimes that means they don’t want you involved in their personal lives. If you notice your child’s mood suddenly change when you ask about what they were doing online, he or she may be keeping something to themselves. [1]\";s:4:\"type\";s:5:\"image\";}i:901;a:7:{s:6:\"status\";s:6:\"active\";s:3:\"src\";s:110:\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/30-Image-Carousel-Child-Safety-Slide-4.jpg\";s:5:\"title\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 4\";s:4:\"link\";s:0:\"\";s:3:\"alt\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 4\";s:7:\"caption\";s:235:\"<strong>Withdraws from friends: </strong>One week they’re best friends and want a sleepover every night, and the next week no one is coming over to your house. Your child may refuse to spend time with friends or age related peers.[1]\";s:4:\"type\";s:5:\"image\";}i:902;a:7:{s:6:\"status\";s:6:\"active\";s:3:\"src\";s:110:\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/30-Image-Carousel-Child-Safety-Slide-5.jpg\";s:5:\"title\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 5\";s:4:\"link\";s:0:\"\";s:3:\"alt\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 5\";s:7:\"caption\";s:205:\"<strong>Stresses about attending school: </strong>Your child may not want to go to school and may start to mention that they hate their classes, their teachers, or some other aspect of their academics. [1]\";s:4:\"type\";s:5:\"image\";}i:903;a:7:{s:6:\"status\";s:6:\"active\";s:3:\"src\";s:110:\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/30-Image-Carousel-Child-Safety-Slide-6.jpg\";s:5:\"title\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 6\";s:4:\"link\";s:0:\"\";s:3:\"alt\";s:50:\"30 – Image Carousel – Child Safety – Slide 6\";s:7:\"caption\";s:234:\"<strong>Displays depression-like symptoms:</strong> Cyberbullying can take a huge emotional toll on a young individual. You might notice that your child eats less, has a hard time sleeping, or becomes irritated over little things. [1]\";s:4:\"type\";s:5:\"image\";}i:1010;a:7:{s:6:\"status\";s:6:\"active\";s:3:\"src\";s:109:\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/201