nline-privacy/finances-rules.aspx\">http://www.microsoft.com/security/online-privacy/finances-rules.aspx<br /></a>5. Federal Trade Commission. (2012, July). <em>“How to Keep Your Personal Information Secure.”</em>  <a href=\"http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0272-how-keep-your-personal-information-secure\">http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0272-how-keep-your-personal-information-secure</a></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383474[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Off the Record: 6 Tips to Protect Your Personal Information Online','','inherit','open','open','','289-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 20:51:33','2014-07-18 20:51:33','',289,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/289-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(746,8,'2014-07-18 20:52:18','2014-07-18 20:52:18','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-485\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/WhereIsMyData_Infographic_hires_060311.jpg\" alt=\"DM132_D5535_WhereIsMyData_Infographic 2\" width=\"800\" height=\"674\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Where did I put my keys? Where on earth did my cellphone go? Did I leave my purse in the car?</em></span></p>\r\n<p>You ask yourself these questions every day, but do you ever wonder, <em>“Where is my data?” </em>If not, it’s a question you should start asking! Having this knowledge allows you to keep better track of your personal information.</p>\r\n<p>We can’t help ourselves. It’s become commonplace to depend on apps, websites and a slew of online resources to buy items, review bank account information and send emails every day. Anytime you enter your email address, connect on Facebook, or make an online purchase with your credit card, you are transmitting personally identifiable information that could end up in the wrong hands.</p>\r\n<p>And sometimes, it does.</p>\r\n<p>The vast majority of identity theft incidents—about 85 percent—involve the fraudulent use of accessible account information. An average of 12 million Americans fall victim to identity fraud annually.<sup>1</sup> And in 2013, financial losses totaling $21 billion were attributed to cybercrime.<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p>If your data is lost or stolen, the effects can be stressful and devastating. MetLife Defender is a proactive, comprehensive solution that will protect your data and help you avoid these risks.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll in MetLife Defender today</a> </strong>so we can monitor your information and keep you safe online. </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Bureau of Justice Statistics. http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821. Retrieved February 2014.</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. Javelin Strategy &amp; Research. <em>2013 Identity Theft Fraud Statistics from Statistic Brain, U.S. Department of Justice</em>, 2013.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0514375772[exp0515][All States][DC]</span></p>','Where is Your Data?','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 20:52:18','2014-07-18 20:52:18','',419,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/419-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(747,8,'2014-07-18 20:54:49','2014-07-18 20:54:49','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-316\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/1839373051-e1404941760260.jpg\" alt=\"test2\" width=\"795\" height=\"530\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>You received a bill for tonsillitis surgery, but you’ve never even had a sore throat. You haven’t been sick in months, but you were charged for prescription drugs. This is medical identity theft and unfortunately, it accounted for 43 percent of all identity theft incidents reported in 2013.<sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p>Medical identity theft happens when an unauthorized person uses your personal information for consultations, surgical procedures, prescription drugs and other billable healthcare services. You wouldn’t imagine medical identity theft to be as prevalent as personal identity theft, however, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services estimates that somewhere between 27.8 and 67.7 million individuals’ medical records have been breached since 2009.<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defender will monitor and protect your medical information in real time, but here are some tips to help keep you in control:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>KEEP TABS:</strong> Organize and keep track of your medical ID card(s). Put them away after presenting them to the provider, never leave them within view of others, and ensure the information is stored in your Member Dashboard for online protection.<sup>3</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>CHECK YOUR BALANCE:</strong> Review your Explanation of Benefits statements to ensure you have not been billed for services you did not receive.<sup>4</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>KEEP IT CONFIDENTIAL:</strong> Talk to your doctor about confidentiality. Ask how your health information is used and what kind of information is necessary for insurance purposes.</li>\r\n<li><strong>KNOW THE ROPES:</strong> If you provide personal information for surveys, health screenings, health websites or online forums, be sure to review privacy policies to see how your information will be used.<sup>4</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>ALWAYS DOUBLE CHECK:</strong> Verify the medical information stored in your Member Dashboard. If you recently changed insurance or added a dependent, now is a good time to make sure we have the new info.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Not sure what to do next? <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Click here to enroll in MetLife Defender</a> today!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Identity Theft Resource Cente(2014, February 20). <em>ITRC 2013 Breach List Tops 600 in 2013</em>. Identity Theft Resource Center. Retrieved from http://www.idtheftcenter.org/ITRC-Surveys-Studies/2013-data-breaches.html </span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. Ollove, Michael. (2014, February 7). <em>The Rise of Medical Identity Theft in Healthcare</em>. Kaiser Health News. Retrieved from http://www.kaiserhealthnews.org/stories/2014/february/07/rise-of-indentity-theft.aspx</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">3. Pennsylvania Attorney General. <em>Consumers</em>. Retrieved from http://www.attorneygeneral.gov/consumers.aspx?id=1645</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">4. Federal Trade Commission. (2012, August). <em>Medical Identity Theft</em>. Retrieved from http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0171-medical-identity-theft</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383470[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Healthy Living: 5 Tips to Protect Your Medical Information','','inherit','open','open','','297-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 20:54:49','2014-07-18 20:54:49','',297,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/297-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(748,8,'2014-07-18 20:55:08','2014-07-18 20:55:08','<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Bullying isn’t a new phenomenon – it has existed for years. In fact, many of us can still remember the name of our own schoolyard bully.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">But modern technology and social media have spawned a new, more prevalent form of bullying known as cyberbullying.  Like the instances you remember from the playground, cyberbullying can having lasting effects on today’s children and parents alike. Education and an open dialogue within families can go a long way. Answer these questions to see how up-to-date you are on the topic of cyberbullying:</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">[playbuzz-game game=https://www.playbuzz.com/meganahearn10/cyberbullying-just-a-buzzword-or-a-legitimate-problem]</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">As a parent, it’s important to keep the lines of communication open and create a safe, non-judgmental environment where your child feels he or she can share issues as they come up. It’s also important to keep tabs on the various platforms your children are using as 90% of all bullying originates on the popular networking sites of Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Through MetLife Defender’s App, parents can receive real-time alerts when their child is a suspected victim of online threats or cyberbullying. Trusting MetLife Defender and utilizing the anti-cyberbullying features does not mean you are spying on your children; rather you are proactively protecting them against a wide range of online threats including cyberbullying, ID theft, and the appropriation of their financial and personal information.</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>Sign up for MetLife Defender</strong></a><strong> and take advantage of the easy-to-install app. </strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> L0614379031[exp0615][All States][DC]</span></p>','Cyberbullying: Just a Buzzword or a Legitimate Problem?','','inherit','open','open','','661-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 20:55:08','2014-07-18 20:55:08','',661,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/661-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(749,8,'2014-07-18 20:55:29','2014-07-18 20:55:29','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-469\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/14-Article-Good-Habits-Mean-Safety-Long-Term-3000x2000.jpg\" alt=\"14 - Article - Good Habits Mean Safety Long Term\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" /><br /> </p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Tips for protecting our tech-savvy kids from online identity theft</em></span></p>\r\n<p>LOL. OMG. TTYS.  If you have kids, you probably know what we’re talking about. And while this innocent cyber language can be fun, it’s also a clue to how much time our children are spending online and the risks involved with it.</p>\r\n<p>A 2013 poll showed that the average tween and teen spent at least five hours per day online, and 86% of them believed social networking sites to be safe.<sup>1</sup> Almost all of their parents agreed, but unfortunately, this is not the case.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Easy as A.B.C.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Predators and cybercriminals are going after an easier target these days: our children. Between cell phones, tablets, and laptops, today’s children are rarely more than a click away from the digital world—even while at school. And stealing a child’s information is easier than you think.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Who are they talking to?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Our children have the world at their fingertips. That also means that they can communicate with a world full of people. And while they may be gaming, chatting, and sharing with “friends,” they could also be interacting with complete strangers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Passwords are only as strong as you make them</strong></p>\r\n<p>We often create passwords that have to do with our personal life, referencing information such as our address, phone number and birth date. Unfortunately, our kids do this too —and the abundance of information on the internet makes it incredibly simple for someone to steal.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Does it really matter? And how much can they find out about my child online?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Absolutely!  Aside from your child’s safety, his or her identity is also at risk. And for that matter, your identity. Imagine finding out that your daughter has a mortgage (unpaid of course) in a faraway state, or that your son has outstanding hospital bills. It seems impossible, but because we typically don’t keep close tabs on what kind of information our children are sharing, identity theft happens. And it’s no laughing matter. Child identity theft can cause huge problems for them down the road when they want to buy a car or apply for student loans.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Protect yourself and your children from online danger</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">MetLife Defender</a> can help by providing constant monitoring, protection, and resources to keep you safe.  <strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll today</a> and start experiencing better online protection for you and your family.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. McAfee.  (2013, June). <em>McAfee Digital Deception Study 2013. </em>Retrieved from: http://www.mcafee.com/us/resources/reports/rp-digital-deception-survey.pdf</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0614379029[exp0615][All States][DC] </span></p>','Your Children: Good Habits Now Mean Safety Long-Term','','inherit','open','open','','466-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 20:55:29','2014-07-18 20:55:29','',466,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/466-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(750,8,'2014-07-18 20:56:35','2014-07-18 20:56:35','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-485\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/WhereIsMyData_Infographic_hires_060311.jpg\" alt=\"DM132_D5535_WhereIsMyData_Infographic 2\" width=\"800\" height=\"674\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Where did I put my keys? Where on earth did my cellphone go? Did I leave my purse in the car?</em></span></p>\r\n<p>You ask yourself these questions every day, but do you ever wonder, <em>“Where is my data?” </em>If not, it’s a question you should start asking! Having this knowledge allows you to keep better track of your personal information.</p>\r\n<p>We can’t help ourselves. It’s become commonplace to depend on apps, websites and a slew of online resources to buy items, review bank account information and send emails every day. Anytime you enter your email address, connect on Facebook, or make an online purchase with your credit card, you are transmitting personally identifiable information that could end up in the wrong hands.</p>\r\n<p>And sometimes, it does.</p>\r\n<p>The vast majority of identity theft incidents—about 85 percent—involve the fraudulent use of accessible account information. An average of 12 million Americans fall victim to identity fraud annually.<sup>1</sup> And in 2013, financial losses totaling $21 billion were attributed to cybercrime.<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p>If your data is lost or stolen, the effects can be stressful and devastating. MetLife Defender is a proactive, comprehensive solution that will protect your data and help you avoid these risks.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll in MetLife Defender today</a></strong> <strong>so we can monitor your information and keep you safe online. </strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Bureau of Justice Statistics. http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821. Retrieved February 2014.</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. Javelin Strategy &amp; Research. <em>2013 Identity Theft Fraud Statistics from Statistic Brain, U.S. Department of Justice</em>, 2013.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0514375772[exp0515][All States][DC]</span></p>','Where is Your Data?','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 20:56:35','2014-07-18 20:56:35','',419,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/419-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(751,8,'2014-07-18 20:56:49','2014-07-18 20:56:49','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-417\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/1784001601-3000x2001.jpg\" alt=\"178400160\" width=\"800\" height=\"534\" /></p>\r\n<p>The busier we get, the more we turn to quick fixes like online shopping, online banking and social media to stay on top of our everyday lives. In 2013, Americans spent more than $262 billion online and approximately 51 percent of U.S. adults were banking online.<sup>1,2</sup> However, with online theft and fraud becoming more sophisticated, it’s important to take precautions to protect ourselves.</p>\r\n<p> Annually, more than 11.5 million Americans fall victim to identity theft, and studies indicate that an average of $4,930 is lost per incident.<sup>3</sup> MetLife Defender is always on guard to make sure you don’t become one of these statistics. Keep the following tips in mind to help educate yourself on what you can do to keep your personal and financial information secure.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>DON’T SHARE YOUR BIRTHDAY</strong>: If all of your Facebook friends can find it with one click, then your birthday probably isn’t as secure as you think. To create a strong, unique password for your financial accounts, make sure you steer away from using easily accessible information like your birthday or family members’ names in your password.</li>\r\n<li><strong>PRACTICE SAFETY FIRST: </strong>If you’re visiting a financial website, make sure you are using secure internet like your home service and not public Wi-Fi.  </li>\r\n<li><strong>DON’T FRET</strong>: You lost your wallet – we’ve all been there. Visit the Lost Wallet Protection [hyperlink to page] page so we can help you recover from the loss and continue safeguarding your information.</li>\r\n<li><strong>DON’T “<em>CLICK HERE”</em>: </strong>If it seems suspicious, it probably is. To ensure every security alert you receive from your financial institution is authentic, check to see if it contains email links or ask you to call phone numbers. If so, cross-check this information with the contact information on your financial institution’s website or visit the website directly to login.<sup>4</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>PLAY DEFENSE:</strong> Is all of your financial information up-to-date on your MetLife Defender Member Dashboard? Take a minute and make sure, so MetLife Defender can proactively protect your financial data.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Need more help? <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll in MetLife Defender</a> today!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Sehgal, Vikram and Jeff Wray. (2013, February 27). Online Retail Forecast, 2012 to 2017. Forrester Research. Retrieved from http://www.forrester.com/US+Online+Retail+Forecast+2009+To+2014/fulltext/-/E-RES56551<a href=\"http://www.forrester.com/US+Online+Retail+Forecast+2009+To+2014/fulltext/-/E-RES56551\"><br /></a>2. Fox, Susannah. (2013, August 7). 51% of U.S. Adults Bank Online. Pew Research. Retrieved from http://www.pewinternet.org/2013/08/07/51-of-u-s-adults-bank-online<a href=\"http://www.pewinternet.org/2013/08/07/51-of-u-s-adults-bank-online/\"><br /></a>3. U.S. Department of Justice, Javelin Strategy  &amp; Research.(2013, June 18). Identity Theft/Fraud Statistics. </span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">4. Federal Trade Commission. (2011, September).“<em>Consumer Information: Phishing.</em>” Retrieved from http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0003-phishing</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383465[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Keep Cybercriminals at Bay: 5 Tips to Protect Your Financial Data and Identity','','inherit','open','open','','416-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 20:56:49','2014-07-18 20:56:49','',416,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/416-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0);
