VALUES
	(752,8,'2014-07-18 21:04:02','2014-07-18 21:04:02','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-315\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/1004805681-e1405100092880.jpg\" alt=\"test 1\" width=\"800\" height=\"1064\" /></p>\r\n<p>From buying new shoes, to connecting with high school buddies, to checking 401(k) account levels - and everything in between - we’re getting used to doing everything online. However, we don’t always think twice when sharing information about ourselves with third parties, and this may put us at risk.  In fact, in 2012, one American fell victim to identity theft every three seconds, and 85 percent of those incidents involved the fraudulent use of information linked to credit cards or bank accounts. <sup>1,2</sup></p>\r\n<p> It can be overwhelming to keep track of – let alone defend against – every digital danger we are exposed to. MetLife Defender makes it simple to safeguard against these threats, but following some simple tips can help keep your digital life intact.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li> <strong>KEEP IT ON A NEED-TO-KNOW BASIS</strong>:Just because there’s a box for it, doesn’t mean you have to fill it out. When shopping online, provide the minimum amount of information necessary to complete your order and be wary of questions that seem unrelated to your purchase.<sup>3</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>SWITCH IT UP</strong>: The password for your bank account should always be different than the password you use for websites where you shop or watch videos. Having multiple passwords can help decrease the chances of others accessing your online accounts.<sup>4</sup>MetLife Defender can help protect your online account logins, so be sure to keep them updated on your Member Dashboard. </li>\r\n<li><strong>DON’T LEAVE A TRACE</strong>:When you no longer need them, shred credit card offers or applications, insurance forms, physician billing statements, voided or deposited checks, and similar sources of personal data.<sup>5</sup> Also, make sure to clear your phone and computer of all personal information before disposing of them, in case they fall into the wrong hands.<sup>5</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>BE A LITTLE MYSTERIOUS</strong>:Keep your personal information private by making sure you never post sensitive items like your Social Security Number, date of birth, address, phone number, or account numbers on social media or other publicly-accessible sites.<sup>5</sup> </li>\r\n<li><strong>DON’T BE AFRAID TO DELETE</strong>: If an email or social media post seems suspicious, delete it or mark it as spam. Do not click on unfamiliar links that could compromise your computer.<sup>5</sup> </li>\r\n<li><strong>STAY ALERT</strong>: As a valued member, MetLife Defender works to protect you 24/7 and will send you real-time alerts if any suspicious activity is detected.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Peace of mind is only a click away. <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll in MetLife Defender</a> today! </strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Pascual, Alphonse and Sarah Miller. (2013, February). 2013 Identity Fraud Report. Javelin Strategy.Retrieved from <a href=\"https://www.javelinstrategy.com/news/1387/92/1\">https://www.javelinstrategy.com/news/1387/92/1<br /></a>2. Harrell, Erika and Lynn Langton. (2013, December 12). <em>“Victims of Identity Theft, 2012.”</em> Bureau of Justice Statistics. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821\">http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821<br /></a>3. Identity Theft Resource Center.<em> “ITRC Fact Sheet 103 Online Shopping.” </em>. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.idtheftcenter.org/index.php/Fact-Sheets/fs-103.html\">http://www.idtheftcenter.org/index.php/Fact-Sheets/fs-103.html<br /></a>4. Microsoft.<em>“Six rules for safer financial transactions online.” </em> Retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.microsoft.com/security/online-privacy/finances-rules.aspx\">http://www.microsoft.com/security/online-privacy/finances-rules.aspx<br /></a>5. Federal Trade Commission. (2012, July). <em>“How to Keep Your Personal Information Secure.”</em>  <a href=\"http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0272-how-keep-your-personal-information-secure\">http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0272-how-keep-your-personal-information-secure</a></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383474[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Off the Record: 6 Tips to Protect Your Personal Information Online','','inherit','open','open','','289-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 21:04:02','2014-07-18 21:04:02','',289,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/289-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(753,7,'2014-07-18 21:06:09','2014-07-18 21:06:09','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-475\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/12-Article-Are-You-Password-Savvy-Image-3000x2297.jpg\" alt=\"12 - Article - Are You Password Savvy Image\" width=\"800\" height=\"613\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Test your smarts!</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>If you’re not an identity thief, it can be hard to think like one! Take this quick quiz to see if you can outsmart a cyber criminal.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #444444;\">[playbuzz-game game=https://www.playbuzz.com/</span>http://www.playbuzz.com/meganahearn10/are-you-password-savvy]</p>\r\n<p><strong>If you got all three correct – good for you!</strong>  You’re well on the way to foiling a cyber criminal. </p>\r\n<p><strong>If you got fewer than three right, don’t be alarmed.</strong>  But do take a hard look at your passwords and make some changes. </p>\r\n<p><strong>Check out more resources on strong passwords and online safety in the <a href=\"http://www.metlifedefender.com/toolsandtips\">Tools &amp; Tips</a> section of MetLifeDefender.com and sign up for a free trial!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Are You Password Savvy?','','inherit','open','open','','453-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 21:06:09','2014-07-18 21:06:09','',453,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/453-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(754,8,'2014-07-18 21:11:44','2014-07-18 21:11:44','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-469\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/14-Article-Good-Habits-Mean-Safety-Long-Term-3000x2000.jpg\" alt=\"14 - Article - Good Habits Mean Safety Long Term\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" /><br /> </p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Tips for protecting our tech-savvy kids from online identity theft</em></span></p>\r\n<p>LOL. OMG. TTYS.  If you have kids, you probably know what we’re talking about. And while this innocent cyber language can be fun, it’s also a clue to how much time our children are spending online and the risks involved with it.</p>\r\n<p>A 2013 poll showed that the average tween and teen spent at least five hours per day online, and 86% of them believed social networking sites to be safe.<sup>1</sup> Almost all of their parents agreed, but unfortunately, this is not the case.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Easy as A.B.C.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Predators and cybercriminals are going after an easier target these days: our children. Between cell phones, tablets, and laptops, today’s children are rarely more than a click away from the digital world—even while at school. And stealing a child’s information is easier than you think.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Who are they talking to?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Our children have the world at their fingertips. That also means that they can communicate with a world full of people. And while they may be gaming, chatting, and sharing with “friends,” they could also be interacting with complete strangers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Passwords are only as strong as you make them</strong></p>\r\n<p>We often create passwords that have to do with our personal life, referencing information such as our address, phone number and birth date. Unfortunately, our kids do this too —and the abundance of information on the internet makes it incredibly simple for someone to steal.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Does it really matter? And how much can they find out about my child online?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Absolutely!  Aside from your child’s safety, his or her identity is also at risk. And for that matter, your identity. Imagine finding out that your daughter has a mortgage (unpaid of course) in a faraway state, or that your son has outstanding hospital bills. It seems impossible, but because we typically don’t keep close tabs on what kind of information our children are sharing, identity theft happens. And it’s no laughing matter. Child identity theft can cause huge problems for them down the road when they want to buy a car or apply for student loans.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Protect yourself and your children from online danger</strong></p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defender can help by providing constant monitoring, protection, and resources to keep you safe.  <strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll today</a> and start experiencing better online protection for you and your family.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. McAfee.  (2013, June). <em>McAfee Digital Deception Study 2013. </em>Retrieved from: http://www.mcafee.com/us/resources/reports/rp-digital-deception-survey.pdf</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0614379029[exp0615][All States][DC] </span></p>','Your Children: Good Habits Now Mean Safety Long-Term','','inherit','open','open','','466-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 21:11:44','2014-07-18 21:11:44','',466,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/466-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(756,7,'2014-07-18 21:13:21','2014-07-18 21:13:21','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-316\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/1839373051-e1404941760260.jpg\" alt=\"test2\" width=\"795\" height=\"530\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>You received a bill for tonsillitis surgery, but you’ve never even had a sore throat. You haven’t been sick in months, but you were charged for prescription drugs. This is medical identity theft and unfortunately, it accounted for 43 percent of all identity theft incidents reported in 2013.<sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p>Medical identity theft happens when an unauthorized person uses your personal information for consultations, surgical procedures, prescription drugs and other billable healthcare services. You wouldn’t imagine medical identity theft to be as prevalent as personal identity theft, however, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services estimates that somewhere between 27.8 and 67.7 million individuals’ medical records have been breached since 2009.<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defender will monitor and protect your medical information in real time, but here are some tips to help keep you in control:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>KEEP TABS:</strong> Organize and keep track of your medical ID card(s). Put them away after presenting them to the provider, never leave them within view of others, and ensure the information is stored in your Member Dashboard for online protection.<sup>3</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>CHECK YOUR BALANCE:</strong> Review your Explanation of Benefits statements to ensure you have not been billed for services you did not receive.<sup>4</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>KEEP IT CONFIDENTIAL:</strong> Talk to your doctor about confidentiality. Ask how your health information is used and what kind of information is necessary for insurance purposes.</li>\r\n<li><strong>KNOW THE ROPES:</strong> If you provide personal information for surveys, health screenings, health websites or online forums, be sure to review privacy policies to see how your information will be used.<sup>4</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>ALWAYS DOUBLE CHECK:</strong> Verify the medical information stored in your Member Dashboard. If you recently changed insurance or added a dependent, now is a good time to make sure we have the new info.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Not sure what to do next? <span style=\"color: #ff6600;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">Click here to enroll in MetLife Defender</span></a></span> </span>today!</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Identity Theft Resource Cente(2014, February 20). <em>ITRC 2013 Breach List Tops 600 in 2013</em>. Identity Theft Resource Center. Retrieved from http://www.idtheftcenter.org/ITRC-Surveys-Studies/2013-data-breaches.html </span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. Ollove, Michael. (2014, February 7). <em>The Rise of Medical Identity Theft in Healthcare</em>. Kaiser Health News. Retrieved from http://www.kaiserhealthnews.org/stories/2014/february/07/rise-of-indentity-theft.aspx</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">3. Pennsylvania Attorney General. <em>Consumers</em>. Retrieved from http://www.attorneygeneral.gov/consumers.aspx?id=1645</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">4. Federal Trade Commission. (2012, August). <em>Medical Identity Theft</em>. Retrieved from http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0171-medical-identity-theft</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383470[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Healthy Living: 5 Tips to Protect Your Medical Information','','inherit','open','open','','297-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 21:13:21','2014-07-18 21:13:21','',297,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/297-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
