	(777,8,'2014-07-21 19:26:19','2014-07-21 19:26:19','<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Bullying isn’t a new phenomenon – it has existed for years. In fact, many of us can still remember the name of our own schoolyard bully.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">But modern technology and social media have spawned a new, more prevalent form of bullying known as cyberbullying.  Like the instances you remember from the playground, cyberbullying can having lasting effects on today’s children and parents alike. Education and an open dialogue within families can go a long way. Answer these questions to see how up-to-date you are on the topic of cyberbullying:</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">[playbuzz-game game=https://www.playbuzz.com/meganahearn10/cyberbullying-just-a-buzzword-or-a-legitimate-problem]</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">As a parent, it’s important to keep the lines of communication open and create a safe, non-judgmental environment where your child feels he or she can share issues as they come up. It’s also important to keep tabs on the various platforms your children are using as 90 percent of all bullying originates on the popular networking sites of Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Through MetLife Defender’s Anti Cyberbullying App, parents can receive real-time alerts when their child is a suspected victim of online threats or cyberbullying. Trusting MetLife Defender and utilizing the anti-cyberbullying features does not mean you are spying on your children; rather you are proactively protecting them against a wide range of online threats including cyberbullying, ID theft, and the appropriation of their financial and personal information.</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>Sign up for MetLife Defender</strong></a><strong> and take advantage of the easy-to-install app. \\</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Patchin, J. W. &amp; Hinduja, S. (2010). Cyberbullying and self-esteem. Journal of School Health, 80(12), 614-621. Retrieved from: http://www.cyberbullying.us/cyberbullying_and_self_esteem_research_fact_sheet.pdf</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. Cyber Bullying: Statistics and Tips. I-SAFE America Survey. Retrieved from: http://www.bullyingstatistics.org/content/bullying-statistics.html</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">3. “Cyberbullying FAQ for Teens.” National Crime Prevention Council. http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-faq-for-teens</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> L0614379031[exp0615][All States][DC]</span></p>','Cyberbullying: Just a Buzzword or a Legitimate Problem?','','inherit','open','open','','661-revision-v1','','','2014-07-21 19:26:19','2014-07-21 19:26:19','',661,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/661-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(778,8,'2014-07-21 19:36:27','2014-07-21 19:36:27','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-417\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/1784001601-3000x2001.jpg\" alt=\"178400160\" width=\"800\" height=\"534\" /></p>\r\n<p>The busier we get, the more we turn to quick fixes like online shopping, online banking and social media to stay on top of our everyday lives. In 2013, Americans spent more than $262 billion online and approximately 51 percent of U.S. adults were banking online.<sup>1,2</sup> However, with online theft and fraud becoming more sophisticated, it’s important to take precautions to protect ourselves.</p>\r\n<p>Annually, more than 11.5 million Americans fall victim to identity theft, and studies indicate that an average of $4,930 is lost per incident.<sup>3</sup> MetLife Defender is always on guard to make sure you don’t become one of these statistics. Keep the following tips in mind to help educate yourself on what you can do to keep your personal and financial information secure.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>DON’T SHARE YOUR BIRTHDAY</strong>: If all of your Facebook friends can find it with one click, then your birthday probably isn’t as secure as you think. To create a strong, unique password for your financial accounts, make sure you steer away from using easily accessible information like your birthday or family members’ names in your password.</li>\r\n<li><strong>PRACTICE SAFETY FIRST: </strong>If you’re visiting a financial website, make sure you are using secure Internet like your home service and not public Wi-Fi.  </li>\r\n<li><strong>DON’T “<em>CLICK HERE”</em>: </strong>If it seems suspicious, it probably is. To ensure every security alert you receive from your financial institution is authentic, check to see if it contains email links or asks you to call phone numbers. If so, cross-check this information with the contact information on your financial institution’s website or visit the website directly to login.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Need more help? <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll in MetLife Defender</a> today!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Sehgal, Vikram and Jeff Wray. (2013, February 27). Online Retail Forecast, 2012 to 2017. Forrester Research. Retrieved from http://www.forrester.com/US+Online+Retail+Forecast+2009+To+2014/fulltext/-/E-RES56551<a href=\"http://www.forrester.com/US+Online+Retail+Forecast+2009+To+2014/fulltext/-/E-RES56551\"><br /></a>2. Fox, Susannah. (2013, August 7). 51% of U.S. Adults Bank Online. Pew Research. Retrieved from http://www.pewinternet.org/2013/08/07/51-of-u-s-adults-bank-online<a href=\"http://www.pewinternet.org/2013/08/07/51-of-u-s-adults-bank-online/\"><br /></a>3. U.S. Department of Justice, Javelin Strategy  &amp; Research.(2013, June 18). Identity Theft/Fraud Statistics. </span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">4. Federal Trade Commission. (2011, September).“<em>Consumer Information: Phishing.</em>” Retrieved from http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0003-phishing</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383465[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Keep Cybercriminals at Bay: 3 Tips to Protect Your Financial Data and Identity','','inherit','open','open','','416-revision-v1','','','2014-07-21 19:36:27','2014-07-21 19:36:27','',416,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/416-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
