	(791,7,'2014-07-23 17:14:17','2014-07-23 17:14:17','<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Bullying isn’t a new phenomenon – it has existed for years. In fact, many of us can still remember the name of our own schoolyard bully.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">But modern technology and social media have spawned a new, more prevalent form of bullying known as cyberbullying.  Like the instances you remember from the playground, cyberbullying can having lasting effects on today’s children and parents alike. Education and an open dialogue within families can go a long way. Answer these questions to see how up-to-date you are on the topic of cyberbullying:</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">[playbuzz-game game=https://www.playbuzz.com/meganahearn10/cyberbullying-just-a-buzzword-or-a-legitimate-problem]</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">As a parent, it’s important to keep the lines of communication open and create a safe, non-judgmental environment where your child feels he or she can share issues as they come up. It’s also important to keep tabs on the various platforms your children are using as 90 percent of all bullying originates on the popular networking sites of Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Through MetLife Defender’s Anti Cyberbullying App, parents can receive real-time alerts when their child is a suspected victim of online threats or cyberbullying. Trusting MetLife Defender and utilizing the anti-cyberbullying features does not mean you are spying on your children; rather you are proactively protecting them against a wide range of online threats including cyberbullying, ID theft, and the appropriation of their financial and personal information.</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>Sign up for MetLife Defender</strong></a><strong> and take advantage of the easy-to-install app. </strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Patchin, J. W. &amp; Hinduja, S. (2010). Cyberbullying and self-esteem. Journal of School Health, 80(12), 614-621. Retrieved from: http://www.cyberbullying.us/cyberbullying_and_self_esteem_research_fact_sheet.pdf</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. Cyber Bullying: Statistics and Tips. I-SAFE America Survey. Retrieved from: http://www.bullyingstatistics.org/content/bullying-statistics.html</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">3. “Cyberbullying FAQ for Teens.” National Crime Prevention Council. http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-faq-for-teens</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> L0614379031[exp0615][All States][DC]</span></p>','Cyberbullying: Just a Buzzword or a Legitimate Problem?','','inherit','open','open','','661-revision-v1','','','2014-07-23 17:14:17','2014-07-23 17:14:17','',661,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/661-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
