	(939,8,'2014-07-28 21:21:15','2014-07-28 21:21:15','<p><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-941\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/22-Article-Heartbleed-Image-3000x2250.jpg\" alt=\"22 - Article - Heartbleed Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"2250\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Protecting Your Privacy on the Web</em></span></p>\r\n<p>Eavesdropping on conversations.  Stealing data. Impersonating users.  The elements of a great spy novel? </p>\r\n<p>Sure, but in this case, they’re the results of the recent Heartbleed bug which served as an important wake up call for safer Internet behaviors.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Bug in brief</strong></p>\r\n<p>The infamous 2014 Heartbleed bug took the Internet by storm and potentially exposed millions of usernames and passwords on several of today’s most popular sites.</p>\r\n<p>Unlike large scale data breaches of the past few years, the Heartbleed bug was a new type of breach which affected a code known as OpenSSL. OpenSSL is widely used across websites to encrypt user-provided information on servers and it is estimated that nearly two-thirds of all Internet sites use the code.</p>\r\n<p><strong>So what?</strong></p>\r\n<p>While all this technical Internet talk may leave you scratching your head, what you really need to know is that your information could still be at risk. A new report shows that as many as 300,000 sites are still vulnerable with many failing to implement the patches now that the initial scare is over.<sup>1   </sup>  </p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defender’s security analysts suggest changing and varying your passwords on the following websites that may have been affected, if you haven’t already done so:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>DropBox</li>\r\n<li>Facebook</li>\r\n<li>Flickr</li>\r\n<li>Google</li>\r\n<li>Gmail</li>\r\n<li>Instagram</li>\r\n<li>OkCupid</li>\r\n<li>Tumblr</li>\r\n<li>Yahoo</li>\r\n<li>Yahoo Mail</li>\r\n<li>YouTube</li>\r\n<li>Wikipedia</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>While this does not mean that your information was exposed, it\'s always better to be safe than sorry and avoid incidents of identity theft. </p>\r\n<p>If you are worried that your data is vulnerable, <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>enroll in MetLife Defender</strong></a> to get proactive protection for your financial, medical and personal data online.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup> Erratta Security (2014) Retrieved from: http://blog.erratasec.com/2014/05/300k-servers-vulnerable-to-heartbleed.html#.U7RxypRdXHW</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> L0714383411[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Stop the Heartbleeding','','publish','open','open','','stop-the-heartbleeding','','','2014-08-13 16:20:54','2014-08-13 16:20:54','',0,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/?p=939',0,'post','',0),
