	(977,7,'2014-08-12 17:49:10','2014-08-12 17:49:10','<p><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-832\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/23-Article-Password-Dos-and-Donts-Image-3000x2002.jpg\" alt=\"23 - Article - Password Dos and Donts Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"2002\" />We all know that keeping complex passwords can help keep cybercriminals away from our sensitive information online. But are we taking this advice seriously? The latest findings may surprise you!</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>The most common password in 2013?  123456!</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>That’s according to SplashData – a password management company that compiles an annual report of users’ most common passwords, gathered by data posted by hackers.<sup>1 </sup></p>\r\n<p>The other top passwords for 2013 included “password,” “abc123” and “111111.”</p>\r\n<p>While these passwords are easy to draft and remember, they are also easy to guess. Here are some tips for creating strong passwords:</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Password DON’Ts:</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>While it may seem obvious to some, it clearly isn’t to the majority: </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Don’t use a string of consecutive numbers or letters, especially starting with “1” or “a”</li>\r\n<li>Don’t include the name of the application (i.e., adobe123)</li>\r\n<li>Don’t use your name, address or company information</li>\r\n<li>Don’t save your passwords within a document on your computer</li>\r\n<li>If the word seems like something your kindergartener could guess – keep thinking!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><em>Password DOs:</em></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Do vary it up, using a different password for each online account</li>\r\n<li>Do get complicated, with randomized numbers to make things complicated for cybercriminals</li>\r\n<li>Do change your passwords every few months</li>\r\n<li>Do stay off the list. If it’s on the list of common passwords above, don’t use it for your password!</li>\r\n<li>Capital letters, symbols, underscores, oh my! Adding in these extra elements can help make any password complex</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Get smart about online safety. <strong>Understand your risks and <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?src=carousel\">enroll in a free trial of MetLife Defender</a> to get comprehensive protection for your personal data online.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup> Splash Data. (2014) <em>Worst Password List.</em> Retrieved from: http://splashdata.com/press/worstpasswords2013.htm</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384030[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Password Dos and Don\'ts','','inherit','open','open','','828-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 17:49:10','2014-08-12 17:49:10','',828,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/828-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(978,7,'2014-08-12 17:49:54','2014-08-12 17:49:54','<p><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-941\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/22-Article-Heartbleed-Image-3000x2250.jpg\" alt=\"22 - Article - Heartbleed Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"2250\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Protecting Your Privacy on the Web</em></span></p>\r\n<p>Eavesdropping on conversations.  Stealing data. Impersonating users.  The elements of a great spy novel? </p>\r\n<p>Sure, but in this case, they’re the results of the recent Heartbleed bug which served as an important wake up call for safer Internet behaviors.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Bug in brief</strong></p>\r\n<p>The infamous 2014 Heartbleed bug took the Internet by storm and potentially exposed millions of usernames and passwords on several of today’s most popular sites.</p>\r\n<p>Unlike large scale data breaches of the past few years, the Heartbleed bug was a new type of breach which affected a code known as OpenSSL. OpenSSL is widely used across websites to encrypt user-provided information on servers and it is estimated that nearly two-thirds of all Internet sites use the code.</p>\r\n<p><strong>So what?</strong></p>\r\n<p>While all this technical Internet talk may leave you scratching your head, what you really need to know is that your information could still be at risk. A new report shows that as many as 300,000 sites are still vulnerable with many failing to implement the patches now that the initial scare is over.<sup>1   </sup>  </p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defender’s security analysts suggest changing and varying your passwords on the following websites that may have been affected, if you haven’t already done so:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>DropBox</li>\r\n<li>Facebook</li>\r\n<li>Flickr</li>\r\n<li>Google</li>\r\n<li>Gmail</li>\r\n<li>Instagram</li>\r\n<li>OkCupid</li>\r\n<li>Tumblr</li>\r\n<li>Yahoo</li>\r\n<li>Yahoo Mail</li>\r\n<li>YouTube</li>\r\n<li>Wikipedia</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>While this does not mean that your information was exposed, it\'s always better to be safe than sorry and avoid incidents of identity theft. </p>\r\n<p>If you are worried that your data is vulnerable, <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>enroll in MetLife Defender</strong></a> to get proactive protection for your financial, medical and personal data online.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup> Erratta Security (2014) Retrieved from: http://blog.erratasec.com/2014/05/300k-servers-vulnerable-to-heartbleed.html#.U7RxypRdXHW</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> L0714383411[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Stop the Heartbleeding','','inherit','open','open','','939-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 17:49:54','2014-08-12 17:49:54','',939,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/939-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(979,7,'2014-08-12 18:02:16','2014-08-12 18:02:16','<p>[soliloquy id=\"899\"]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. National Crime Prevention Council. <i>Cyberbullying: Spotting the Signs</i>. Retrieved from: <a href=\"http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-tip-sheets/NCPC%20Tip%20Sheet%20-%20Spotting%20The%20Signs.pdf\">http</a><a href=\"http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-tip-sheets/NCPC%20Tip%20Sheet%20-%20Spotting%20The%20Signs.pdf\">://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-tip-sheets/NCPC%20Tip%20Sheet%20-%</a><a href=\"http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-tip-sheets/NCPC%20Tip%20Sheet%20-%20Spotting%20The%20Signs.pdf\">20Spotting%20The%20Signs.pdf</a></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt; color: #000000;\">L0714384024[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Top 5 Warning Signs Your Child is Being Cyberbullied','','inherit','open','open','','907-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:02:16','2014-08-12 18:02:16','',907,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/907-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(980,7,'2014-08-12 18:20:23','2014-08-12 18:20:23','<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-933\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/21-Article-Oversharing-Online-Image-3000x1999.jpg\" alt=\"21 - Article - Oversharing Online Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"1999\" /><em>How Much is Too Much?</em></span></p>\n<p>It’s so much easier for our children to connect with friends today. New or old, they are just a click away. With each post, like, check-in or status update, they share a little bit about themselves and their families. Before this bad habit becomes a risk to your entire family, talk to your children about smart and safe behavior online. </p>\n<p><strong>Forever is a long time</strong></p>\n<p>It’s fun to be the first to post a crazy photo from a great weekend or a silly video of friends. But before each post, encourage your child to think about the implications. Sometimes these posts can garner unwanted attention. By the time you try to delete them, it may be too late and the damage can linger for years to come.</p>\n<p><strong>Personal means personal</strong></p>\n<p>About half of teens report that they have shared their email addresses online, about one-third has shared phone numbers, and 15 percent say they’ve published a home address.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p>If this information ends up in the wrong hands, it could be dangerous. Strangers with access to your home address could commit mail fraud, stage a break-in or even use the information to steal your identity. Children may not see the bigger picture, so talk to them about the risks associated with sharing  personal information.</p>\n<p><strong>Privacy is key</strong></p>\n<p>Despite what some may think, what happens on one device doesn’t necessarily stay on that device and could end up on the Internet. Sit down with your children and talk about keeping personal photos personal and not to share via text or social media. It’s important for children to understand that just because they are practicing safe Internet practices, others may not be and could share photos that you don’t want seen by the public.  </p>\n<p><strong>Real-time alerts</strong></p>\n<p>Empower your kids and teens to ask questions about what to share online and to talk to you about any issues with their online life. MetLife Defender is here to help you stay educated on issues affecting your kids online.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Learn more </a>about safe Internet practices and options for enrolling in our Family Plan to get alerts on suspected acts of cyberbullying or predation on your children’s Facebook, Twitter or Instagram accounts.</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup>McAfee. (July, 2014) <em>McAfee’s 2014 Teens and Screens</em>. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens\">http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens</a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384026[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Oversharing Online: TMI!','','inherit','open','open','','931-autosave-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:20:23','2014-08-12 18:20:23','',931,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/931-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
