dia. It’s important for children to understand that just because they are practicing safe Internet practices, others may not be and could share photos that you don’t want seen by the public.  </p>\r\n<p><strong>Real-time alerts</strong></p>\r\n<p>Empower your kids and teens to ask questions about what to share online and to talk to you about any issues with their online life. MetLife Defender is here to help you stay educated on issues affecting your kids online.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/online-child-safety/923/\">Learn more about safe Internet practices</a> and options for enrolling in our Family Plan to get alerts on suspected acts of cyberbullying or predation on your children’s Facebook, Twitter or Instagram accounts.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup>McAfee. (July, 2014) <em>McAfee’s 2014 Teens and Screens</em>. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens\">http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens</a></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384026[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Oversharing Online: TMI!','','inherit','open','open','','931-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:20:58','2014-08-12 18:20:58','',931,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/931-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(982,7,'2014-08-12 18:22:12','2014-08-12 18:22:12','<p> <img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-920\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/20-Article-Online-Child-Predation-7-8-14-Image-2000x3000.jpg\" alt=\"imsis550-173\" width=\"2000\" height=\"3000\" /><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; font-style: italic;\">Tips for Keeping Your Children Safe Online</span></p>\r\n<p>“Never accept a ride from a stranger.”  “Come straight home from school.”  “Don’t talk to strangers.”</p>\r\n<p>If you’re like most parents, you’ve been having similar conversations with your children since they were old enough to talk.  But today, the danger doesn’t just look like a suspicious character in a strange car, it exists online. Today’s technology makes it easier than ever for strangers to target and contact your children. Get up to speed on the dangers they face and talk to your children about being safe online.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The online stranger</strong></p>\r\n<p>It’s simple. “Stranger” equals “no.” It’s easy for anyone to message your son or daughter about his or her favorite sports team, or even pretend to be a mutual friend of relatives. Remind your child if he or she is contacted by a stranger not to respond to the person in question and tell an adult.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Privacy please!</strong></p>\r\n<p>Privacy nowadays is more than shutting your door or closing the blinds, online privacy is key too!  Read the privacy settings on all social media sites and decide with your child exactly how much information is best to share. Educate your child about what could happen if sensitive information is made available to strangers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>A friend of a friend’s friend doesn’t have to be a friend of yours</strong></p>\r\n<p>Online sites are great at suggesting “people you might know.”  Children and teens enjoy having large social networks, which makes it intriguing to accept friend requests from people who are friends with their social groups. It is important to review that just because an individual is a friend or relative of a friend, does not mean it is safe.  While it can be fun for your child to connect the dots back from the friend she met at the beach last summer to your second cousin’s tennis instructor’s daughter, it’s an activity best done by you and your child together.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Taking control</strong></p>\r\n<p>Keeping tabs on your child’s digital life can be overwhelming, even if you are armed with the best tips. MetLife Defender’s Family Plan is a great option to monitor your child’s social media accounts when you can’t. It consistently scans your child’s Facebook, Twitter and Instagram accounts to flag any suspected acts of predation and cyberbullying. <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>Learn more about your options here.</strong></a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384029[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','A Lot More Than Child\'s Play','','inherit','open','open','','923-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:22:12','2014-08-12 18:22:12','',923,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/923-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(983,7,'2014-08-12 18:23:05','2014-08-12 18:23:05','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-469\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/14-Article-Good-Habits-Mean-Safety-Long-Term-3000x2000.jpg\" alt=\"14 - Article - Good Habits Mean Safety Long Term\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Tips for Protecting Our Tech-Savvy Kids from Online Identity Theft</em></span></p>\r\n<p>LOL. OMG. TTYS.  If you have kids, you probably know what we’re talking about. And while this innocent cyber language can be fun, it’s also a clue to how much time our children are spending online and the risks involved with it.</p>\r\n<p>A 2013 poll showed that the average tween and teen spent at least five hours per day online, and 86 percent of them believed social networking sites to be safe.<sup>1</sup> Almost all of their parents agreed, but unfortunately, this is not the case.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Easy as A.B.C.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Predators and cybercriminals are going after an easier target these days: our children. Between cell phones, tablets, and laptops, today’s children are rarely more than a click away from the digital world—even while at school. And stealing a child’s information is easier than you think.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Who are they talking to?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Our children have the world at their fingertips. That also means that they can communicate with a world full of people. And while they may be gaming, chatting, and sharing with “friends,” they could also be interacting with complete strangers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Passwords are only as strong as you make them</strong></p>\r\n<p>We often create passwords that have to do with our personal life, referencing information such as our address, phone number and birth date. Unfortunately, our kids do this too —and the abundance of information on the Internet makes it incredibly simple for someone to steal.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Does it really matter? And how much can they find out about my child online?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Absolutely!  Aside from your child’s safety, his or her identity is also at risk. And for that matter, your identity. Imagine finding out that your daughter has a mortgage (unpaid of course) in a faraway state, or that your son has outstanding hospital bills. It seems impossible, but because we typically don’t keep close tabs on what kind of information our children are sharing, identity theft happens. And it’s no laughing matter. Child identity theft can cause huge problems for them down the road when they want to buy a car or apply for student loans.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Protect yourself and your children from online danger</strong></p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defender can help by providing constant monitoring, protection, and resources to keep you safe.  <strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll today</a> and start experiencing better online protection for you and your family.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. McAfee.  (2013, June). <em>McAfee Digital Deception Study 2013. </em>Retrieved from: http://www.mcafee.com/us/resources/reports/rp-digital-deception-survey.pdf</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0614379029[exp0615][All States][DC] </span></p>','Your Children: Good Habits Now Mean Safety Long-Term','','inherit','open','open','','466-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:23:05','2014-08-12 18:23:05','',466,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/466-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
