	(1002,7,'2014-08-13 21:42:46','2014-08-13 21:42:46','','MLD-Med-ID-Theft-Snapshot-A-081314','','inherit','open','open','','mld-med-id-theft-snapshot-a-081314','','','2014-08-13 21:42:46','2014-08-13 21:42:46','',0,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/MLD-Med-ID-Theft-Snapshot-A-081314.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),
	(1003,7,'2014-08-13 22:42:55','2014-08-13 22:42:55','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-315\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/1004805681-e1405100092880.jpg\" alt=\"test 1\" width=\"800\" height=\"1064\" /></p>\r\n<p>From buying new shoes, to connecting with high school buddies, to checking 401(k) account levels - and everything in between - we’re getting used to doing everything online. However, we don’t always think twice when sharing information about ourselves with third parties, and this may put us at risk.  In fact, in 2012, one American fell victim to identity theft every three seconds, and 85 percent of those incidents involved the fraudulent use of information linked to credit cards or bank accounts. <sup>1,2</sup></p>\r\n<p>It can be overwhelming to keep track of – let alone defend against – every digital danger we are exposed to. MetLife Defender makes it simple to safeguard against these threats, but following some simple tips can help keep your digital life intact.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li> <strong>KEEP IT ON A NEED-TO-KNOW BASIS</strong>: Just because there’s a box for it, doesn’t mean you have to fill it out. When shopping online, provide the minimum amount of information necessary to complete your order and be wary of questions that seem unrelated to your purchase.<sup>3</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>SWITCH IT UP</strong>: The password for your bank account should always be different than the password you use for websites where you shop or watch videos. Having multiple passwords can help decrease the chances of others accessing your online accounts.<sup>4 </sup>MetLife Defender can help protect your online account logins, so be sure to keep them updated on your Member Dashboard. </li>\r\n<li><strong>DON’T LEAVE A TRACE</strong>: When you no longer need them, shred credit card offers or applications, insurance forms, physician billing statements, voided or deposited checks, and similar sources of personal data.<sup>5</sup> Also, make sure to clear your phone and computer of all personal information before disposing of them, in case they fall into the wrong hands.<sup>5</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>BE A LITTLE MYSTERIOUS</strong>: Keep your personal information private by making sure you never post sensitive items like your Social Security number, date of birth, address, phone number, or account numbers on social media or other publicly-accessible sites.<sup>5</sup> </li>\r\n<li><strong>DON’T BE AFRAID TO DELETE</strong>: If an email or social media post seems suspicious, delete it or mark it as spam. Do not click on unfamiliar links that could compromise your computer.<sup>5</sup> </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Peace of mind is only a click away. <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll in MetLife Defender</a> today! </strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Pascual, Alphonse and Sarah Miller. (2013, February). 2013 Identity Fraud Report. Javelin Strategy.Retrieved from https://www.javelinstrategy.com/news/1387/92/1<br />2. Harrell, Erika and Lynn Langton. (2013, December 12). <em>“Victims of Identity Theft, 2012.”</em> Bureau of Justice Statistics. Retrieved from http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821<br />3. Identity Theft Resource Center.<em> “ITRC Fact Sheet 103 Online Shopping.” </em>. Retrieved from http://www.idtheftcenter.org/index.php/Fact-Sheets/fs-103.html<br />4. Microsoft.<em>“Six rules for safer financial transactions online.” </em> Retrieved from http://www.microsoft.com/security/online-privacy/finances-rules.aspx<br />5. Federal Trade Commission. (2012, July). <em>“How to Keep Your Personal Information Secure.”</em>  http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0272-how-keep-your-personal-information-secure</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383474[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Off the Record: 6 Tips to Protect Your Personal Information Online','','inherit','open','open','','289-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 22:42:55','2014-08-13 22:42:55','',289,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/289-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(1004,7,'2014-08-13 22:43:22','2014-08-13 22:43:22','<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-933\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/21-Article-Oversharing-Online-Image-3000x1999.jpg\" alt=\"21 - Article - Oversharing Online Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"1999\" /><em>How Much is Too Much?</em></span></p>\r\n<p>It’s so much easier for our children to connect with friends today. New or old, they are just a click away. With each post, like, check-in or status update, they share a little bit about themselves and their families. Before this bad habit becomes a risk to your entire family, talk to your children about smart and safe behavior online. </p>\r\n<p><strong>Forever is a long time</strong></p>\r\n<p>It’s fun to be the first to post a crazy photo from a great weekend or a silly video of friends. But before each post, encourage your child to think about the implications. Sometimes these posts can garner unwanted attention. By the time you try to delete them, it may be too late and the damage can linger for years to come.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Personal means personal</strong></p>\r\n<p>About half of teens report that they have shared their email addresses online, about one-third has shared phone numbers, and 15 percent say they’ve published a home address.<sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p>If this information ends up in the wrong hands, it could be dangerous. Strangers with access to your home address could commit mail fraud, stage a break-in or even use the information to steal your identity. Children may not see the bigger picture, so talk to them about the risks associated with sharing  personal information.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Privacy is key</strong></p>\r\n<p>Despite what some may think, what happens on one device doesn’t necessarily stay on that device and could end up on the Internet. Sit down with your children and talk about keeping personal photos personal and not to share via text or social media. It’s important for children to understand that just because they are practicing safe Internet practices, others may not be and could share photos that you don’t want seen by the public.  </p>\r\n<p><strong>Real-time alerts</strong></p>\r\n<p>Empower your kids and teens to ask questions about what to share online and to talk to you about any issues with their online life. MetLife Defender is here to help you stay educated on issues affecting your kids online.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/online-child-safety/923/\">Learn more about safe Internet practices</a> and options for enrolling in our Family Plan to get alerts on suspected acts of cyberbullying or predation on your children’s Facebook, Twitter or Instagram accounts.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup>McAfee. (July, 2014) <em>McAfee’s 2014 Teens and Screens</em>. Retrieved from http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384026[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Oversharing Online: TMI!','','inherit','open','open','','931-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 22:43:22','2014-08-13 22:43:22','',931,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/931-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(1005,7,'2014-08-13 22:44:26','2014-08-13 22:44:26','<p>[soliloquy id=\"899\"]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. National Crime Prevention Council. <i>Cyberbullying: Spotting the Signs</i>. Retrieved from: http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-tip-sheets/NCPC%20Tip%20Sheet%20-%20Spotting%20The%20Signs.pdf</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt; color: #000000;\">L0714384024[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Top 5 Warning Signs Your Child is Being Cyberbullied','','inherit','open','open','','907-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 22:44:26','2014-08-13 22:44:26','',907,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/907-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(1006,7,'2014-08-13 22:45:50','2014-08-13 22:45:50','<p><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-839\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/17-Article-Prescription-Fraud-7-8-14-Image-3000x2151.jpg\" alt=\"17 - Article - Prescription Fraud 7 8 14 Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"2151\" />Terri arrives at the emergency room after a car accident.  Doctors immediately review her electronic medical records. They note the prescription drugs she’s been taking, and make decisions about her care based on that information. The problem: Terri’s not taking any drugs.</p>\n<p>Peter calls his insurance company to inquire about the coverage of his new cholesterol medication. The provider informs Peter that coverage of that medication has been denied because he is currently being prescribed a different brand of cholesterol medicine. But there is a bigger issue for Peter – he’s not taking any cholesterol prescription pills now. </p>\n<p>Terri and Peter are victims of prescription and medical fraud, and this type of theft is on the uptick in the United States.  1.84 million people were victims of medical identity fraud in 2013 with the out-of-pocket cost to consumers reaching $12.3 billion.<sup>1  </sup>  </p>\n<p>The costs of prescription fraud are personal and financial. Correcting medical records, receiving the wrong treatment, clearing your name, and paying for services you never received are time-consuming, frustrating and often costly experiences.</p>\n<h3 style=\"margin: 0 139px 20px 20px;\">Here are 5 tips to help protect yourself and your family against prescription identity theft:</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Never buy prescriptions from unauthorized websites.</li>\n<li>Carefully review all insurance bills and Explanation of Benefits statements that come in the mail. Immediately report charges for services you have not received.</li>\n<li>Keep medical bills and receipts in a secured location, and only for as long as you need them. Shred all medical paperwork before disposing of it.</li>\n<li>Report lost or stolen insurance cards.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://metlifedefender.com/register/plan/\"><strong>Take action</strong></a> and let MetLife Defender proactively monitor your medical identification information so it doesn’t fall into the wrong hands and lead to identity theft.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Ponemon Institute. (2014) <em>2013 Survey on Medical Identity Theft</em>. Retrieved from http://medidfraud.org/2013-survey-on-medical-identity-theft/</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384027[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Prescription Fraud','','inherit','open','open','','837-autosave-v1','','','2014-08-13 22:45:50','2014-08-13 22:45:50','',837,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/837-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
