Shred all medical paperwork before disposing of it.</li>\r\n<li>Report lost or stolen insurance cards.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"https://metlifedefender.com/register/plan/\"><strong>Take action</strong></a> and let MetLife Defender proactively monitor your medical identification information so it doesn’t fall into the wrong hands and lead to identity theft.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Ponemon Institute (2014). <em>2013 Survey on Medical Identity Theft</em>. Retrieved from http://medidfraud.org/2013-survey-on-medical-identity-theft/</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384027[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Prescription Fraud','','inherit','open','open','','837-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 22:46:01','2014-08-13 22:46:01','',837,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/837-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(1008,7,'2014-08-13 22:47:48','2014-08-13 22:47:48','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-409\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/200299065-0011-2258x3000.jpg\" alt=\"200299065-001\" width=\"339\" height=\"450\" /></p>\r\n<p>Their first picture. First steps. First birthday. Today, children don’t just grow up at home, they grow up online. And by the time they can type, they’ll want to connect with their friends on social media sites and surf the Web. But with a greater online presence comes a greater need to protect our children from cyberbullying, child predation and child identity theft. A recent study reported that one in five children will experience cyberbullying before they graduate high school.<sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p>We know that part of a parent’s job is to worry, but you can ease some of that stress by educating yourself on ways to protect your children online with a few helpful tips:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>WATCH AND LEARN</strong>: It is recommended that you keep tabs on how your children use the Internet, and what sites they visit – don’t be afraid to vet sites before your kids go online.<sup>2</sup> Familiarize yourself with the social media sites your children use and who they are connecting with on Facebook, Twitter and Instagram.  Add MetLife Defender protection to their social media accounts through your Family Plan.</li>\r\n<li><strong>JOIN THE SAME TEAM</strong>: Show your children you have confidence in their abilities to use the Internet responsibly. Incorporate their ideas when you work with your children to establish rules about usage.<sup>2</sup> </li>\r\n<li><strong>EDUCATE AND EXPLAIN</strong>: Communicate why online safety is important and why it’s dangerous to post personal information on the Internet. Be an example to your children and make sure your social media profiles are set to private. As your children get older, explain why social media settings should never be open to the public where information and photos are accessible to anyone.<sup>2</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>BUILD TRUST</strong>: Discuss examples with your children about online threats and comments, and ask if they have ever experienced any aggressive behaviors while online. It is recommended that you constantly discuss with your children the benefits of communicating online and offline problems.<sup>3</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>BE AWARE OF THE SCHOOL ZONE</strong>: Find out how your children\'s information is used by their school and ask the school what methods it uses to safeguard records.<sup>4</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>STAY VIGILANT</strong>: Installing social media protection from MetLife Defender will proactively screen your children’s online accounts and alert you in real time if they become a victim to online threats.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Protect your children and <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">enroll in the MetLife Defender Family Plan</a> today!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Patchin, J. W. &amp; Hinduja, S. (2012). Cyberbullying Prevention and Response: Expert Perspectives.  New York: Routledge.</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. StopBullying.gov<em>. Prevent Cyberbullying.</em> Retrieved from http://www.stopbullying.gov/cyberbullying/prevention/<a href=\"http://www.stopbullying.gov/cyberbullying/prevention/\"><br /></a>3. National Crime Prevention Council.<em>What Parents Can Do About Cyberbullying.</em> Retrieved from http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/stop-cyberbullying<a href=\"http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/stop-cyberbullying\"><br /></a>4. Federal Trade Commission. (2012, August). <em>Child Identity Theft.</em> Retrieved from http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0040-child-identity-theft</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"> </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383466[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Level the Playing Field: 6 Tips to Keep Your Children Safe Online','','inherit','open','open','','408-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 22:47:48','2014-08-13 22:47:48','',408,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/408-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(1009,7,'2014-08-13 22:48:34','2014-08-13 22:48:34','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-472\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/15-Article-Medical-Identity-Theft-Inconvenient-Prevalent-and-Dangerous-Image-3000x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Paying For Healthcare With Credit Card\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" /></p>\r\n<p>Many of us go to great lengths to protect ourselves online and off—using unique passwords, only visiting secure sites, and shredding important documents. But do you ever think twice about the safety of your medical information?</p>\r\n<p>Recent statistics gathered by the Identity Theft Resource Center show that 43 percent of all identity theft reported in 2013 was medical identity theft.<sup>1</sup> What does medical identity theft look like? The following highlights example threats to your medical information and introduces precautions you can take to ensure your information is safe.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The bill for surgery … that you didn’t have!</strong></p>\r\n<p>Your first alert will generally appear in your health insurance Explanation of Benefits in the form of an unknown code. The code, representing a prescription for OxyContin or Viagra, will be there as a reminder of the surgery recovery unbeknownst to you. In either case, neither you nor anyone else in your family was the patient, meaning that someone else received medical services under your name. Aside from the financial burden, this also means you may not be eligible for that same surgery should you actually need it.  </p>\r\n<p><strong>The prescription that’s already been refilled</strong></p>\r\n<p>On your trip to the pharmacy to refill your monthly prescription, you find that it’s already been picked up. You meander home expecting another family member to have stopped by the pharmacy, except neither you nor your family did so. What happened to your prescription? And who could have picked it up? Unfortunately someone else might be using your meds or benefitting from reselling them. </p>\r\n<p><strong>The faulty info</strong></p>\r\n<p>Imagine that you’re getting pre-screened before a scheduled surgery. However, as nurses verify key information with you, you realize the file is all wrong—from blood type to medical history. This is a scenario where someone else could have had access to your files and changed the data to reflect their own personal information. Although it may only be troublesome in this case, it could be fatal if you needed urgent treatment.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Give your medical information a check up</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Ask!</strong> Your doctor’s office requires a lot of personal information, from insurance information, to your phone number, to your Social Security number, family names, birthdays, and even credit card information. Make sure you ask how they store the data and what information is consistently kept on file. Research shows that medical office employees are often allowed to access information from personal devices that may not be protected against hacking.<sup>2</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>Dig deep</strong>. While your benefit statements from your insurance company can be complicated, don’t just set them aside. Read what you’re being billed for, including the physician and date of service. This way, you can catch a problem early on and take the appropriate action to remedy the situation.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Protect</strong>. Give medical insurance cards and flexible spending account credit cards to appropriate personnel only and keep them safely tucked away when not in use.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Increase your dose of security</strong></p>\r\n<p>There is a substantial amount of personal and medical information that you need to keep track of and it can oftentimes be overwhelming; to assist you in protecting your data, enroll in MetLife Defender—a comprehensive and proactive approach to managing and securing your and your family’s health information. MetLife Defender gives you an enhanced layer of protection against medical identity theft and medical fraud through specialized services designed to specifically protect your personal health information.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/?gclid=CjwKEAjw9LKeBRDurOugs43jnlgSJACUXqHx78H5vVXI0Me7QgxKj5yz_7R06jbnbCsR3lp4d4-EDhoCqjfw_wcB\">Visit MetLife Defender</a> and see how you can enroll today!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Ollove, Michael. (2014, February 7). <em>The Rise of Medical Identity Theft in Healthcare</em>. Kaiser Health News.Retrieved from: http://www.kaiserhealthnews.org/stories/2014/february/07/rise-of-indentity-theft.asp</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. Levin, Adam. (2014, March 17). <em>Medical Identity Theft: Does the Health Care Industry Think It\'s Too Big for Its Breaches?</em>. The Ponemon Institute. Retrieved from  http://www.ponemon.org/blog/fourth-annual-benchmark-study-on-patient-privacy-and-data-security</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div id=\"imcontent\" dir=\"ltr\"><span dir=\"ltr\" style=\"color: #000000; font-size: 8pt;\">L0614380272[exp0615][All States][DC]</span></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Medical Identity Theft: Inconvenient, Prevalent and Dangerous','','inherit','open','open','','460-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 22:48:34','2014-08-13 22:48:34','',460,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/460-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
